1
00:01:14,452 --> 00:01:16,745
Thank you very much, sir.

2
00:01:16,746 --> 00:01:18,997
You did a wonderful job. Wonderful.

3
00:01:21,459 --> 00:01:22,959
We did it, Pete. We did it.

4
00:01:24,962 --> 00:01:26,755
For a moment, we had our doubts.

5
00:01:26,756 --> 00:01:30,258
To continue, you've listened
to a long and complex case...

6
00:01:30,259 --> 00:01:32,135
murder in the first degree.

7
00:01:32,136 --> 00:01:37,182
A premeditated murder is the most serious
charge tried in our criminal courts.

8
00:01:37,183 --> 00:01:39,017
You've listened to the testimony.

9
00:01:39,018 --> 00:01:42,020
You've had the law read to you and
interpreted as it applies in this case.

10
00:01:42,021 --> 00:01:46,124
It's now your duty to sit down and try
and separate the facts from the fancy.

11
00:01:46,942 --> 00:01:50,587
One man is dead. Another
man's life is at stake.

12
00:01:51,280 --> 00:01:55,366
If there's a reasonable doubt in your
minds as to the guilt of the accused...

13
00:01:55,367 --> 00:01:57,368
a reasonable doubt...

14
00:01:57,369 --> 00:02:00,246
then you must bring me
a verdict of not guilty.

15
00:02:00,247 --> 00:02:02,207
Now if, however, there's
no reasonable doubt...

16
00:02:02,208 --> 00:02:06,185
then you must in good conscience
find the accused guilty.

17
00:02:07,213 --> 00:02:11,424
However you decide, your
verdict must be unanimous.

18
00:02:11,425 --> 00:02:14,886
In the event that you find
the accused guilty...

19
00:02:14,887 --> 00:02:18,306
the bench will not entertain
a recommendation for mercy.

20
00:02:18,307 --> 00:02:21,601
The death sentence is
mandatory in this case.

21
00:02:21,602 --> 00:02:25,413
You're faced with a grave responsibility.
Thank you, gentlemen.

22
00:02:27,316 --> 00:02:29,459
The alternate jurors are excused.

23
00:02:35,366 --> 00:02:37,467
The jury will now retire.

24
00:04:35,361 --> 00:04:37,462
Try this one.
See if I can get it...

25
00:04:38,697 --> 00:04:40,548
It's a muggy day.

26
00:04:43,702 --> 00:04:46,162
Hey. Oh, oh.

27
00:04:58,133 --> 00:05:00,301
- Piece of gum?
- No, thanks.

28
00:05:00,302 --> 00:05:02,470
This thing is...

29
00:05:02,471 --> 00:05:04,197
...move it.

30
00:05:05,724 --> 00:05:07,976
- Come on, I'll give you a hand.
- Give me a hand with that.

31
00:05:07,977 --> 00:05:09,410
That's it.

32
00:05:14,942 --> 00:05:16,651
- You know something?
- Yeah?

33
00:05:16,652 --> 00:05:18,486
I called the weather
bureau this morning.

34
00:05:18,487 --> 00:05:20,488
This is gonna be the
hottest day of the year.

35
00:05:20,489 --> 00:05:22,156
Could be.

36
00:05:22,157 --> 00:05:24,158
Boy, you'd think they'd at least
air-condition these places.

37
00:05:24,159 --> 00:05:27,578
- What is your name, sir?
- Oh, it's, uh... That one, yeah.

38
00:05:27,579 --> 00:05:29,080
Thank you very much.

39
00:05:29,081 --> 00:05:31,916
Okay, gentlemen, everybody's here.

40
00:05:31,917 --> 00:05:34,836
Now, if there's anything you want,
I'll be right outside the door.

41
00:05:34,837 --> 00:05:37,188
- Just knock.
- Okay, thanks. We will.

42
00:05:49,601 --> 00:05:50,893
Good morning.

43
00:05:50,894 --> 00:05:52,437
I never knew they locked the door.

44
00:05:52,438 --> 00:05:54,705
Sure they lock the door.
What'd you think?

45
00:05:55,691 --> 00:05:58,209
I don't know. It just
never occurred to me.

46
00:05:59,737 --> 00:06:01,612
What's that for?

47
00:06:01,613 --> 00:06:03,573
Oh, I thought we might
want to vote by ballot.

48
00:06:03,574 --> 00:06:06,325
Great idea. Maybe we can
get him elected senator.

49
00:06:08,495 --> 00:06:10,346
Just in case, you know.

50
00:06:13,751 --> 00:06:15,960
- How'd you like it?
- Oh, I don't know.

51
00:06:15,961 --> 00:06:17,712
It was pretty interesting.

52
00:06:17,713 --> 00:06:19,756
Yeah? I almost fell asleep.

53
00:06:19,757 --> 00:06:22,425
I mean, I've never
been on a jury before.

54
00:06:22,426 --> 00:06:25,236
No? I've sat on many juries.

55
00:06:26,305 --> 00:06:29,307
What gets me is the way those
lawyers talk and talk and talk...

56
00:06:29,308 --> 00:06:31,559
even when it's an open-and-shut
case like this one.

57
00:06:31,560 --> 00:06:33,352
Did you ever hear so
much talk about nothin'?

58
00:06:33,353 --> 00:06:35,313
Well, I guess they're entitled.

59
00:06:35,314 --> 00:06:37,874
Yeah. They're entitled.
It's the system, but...

60
00:06:38,984 --> 00:06:43,154
If you ask me, I'd slap those tough kids
down before they start any trouble.

61
00:06:43,155 --> 00:06:45,323
It would save us a lot
of time and money.

62
00:06:45,324 --> 00:06:46,949
- Hey, let's get started, huh?
- That's a good idea.

63
00:06:46,950 --> 00:06:49,660
Yeah, let's get goin', huh? We
probably all got things to do here.

64
00:06:49,661 --> 00:06:51,434
I figured we'd start out
with a five-minute break.

65
00:06:51,460 --> 00:06:52,789
There's one gentleman
in the bathroom.

66
00:06:52,790 --> 00:06:53,831
Mr. Foreman.

67
00:06:53,832 --> 00:06:56,709
- Are, uh... Are we gonna sit in order?
- Gee, I don't know.

68
00:06:56,710 --> 00:06:58,561
I, uh... Well, I guess so.

69
00:07:03,467 --> 00:07:05,009
Uh, you're in my seat.

70
00:07:05,010 --> 00:07:07,111
- Oh. Excuse me.
- That's all right.

71
00:07:09,556 --> 00:07:11,407
Hey, that's not a bad view, huh?

72
00:07:14,937 --> 00:07:17,480
What did you think of the case?

73
00:07:17,481 --> 00:07:19,607
I mean, it had a lot
of interest for me.

74
00:07:19,608 --> 00:07:22,835
No real... dead spots.
You know what I mean?

75
00:07:23,612 --> 00:07:26,155
I tell you, we were lucky
to get a murder case.

76
00:07:26,156 --> 00:07:28,199
I figured us for an
assault or burglary.

77
00:07:28,200 --> 00:07:30,535
Boy, they can be the dullest.

78
00:07:32,037 --> 00:07:33,412
Hey.

79
00:07:33,413 --> 00:07:35,081
That the Woolworth Building?

80
00:07:35,082 --> 00:07:37,083
That's right.

81
00:07:37,084 --> 00:07:38,751
Isn't that funny?

82
00:07:38,752 --> 00:07:41,212
You know, I've lived here all my life.
I've never been inside that.

83
00:07:41,213 --> 00:07:43,381
If you had to
sort out all that junk...

84
00:07:43,382 --> 00:07:45,550
Like that thing with the movies.

85
00:07:45,551 --> 00:07:48,636
Yeah. You can say that again. And what
about that business with the knife?

86
00:07:48,637 --> 00:07:51,597
I mean, asking grown-up people
to believe that kind of jazz, huh?

87
00:07:51,598 --> 00:07:54,142
Well, I expected that.
You know what we're dealing with.

88
00:07:54,143 --> 00:07:56,686
Yeah, I guess so.

89
00:07:56,687 --> 00:07:58,479
Well, your horn works.
Now try your lights.

90
00:08:00,065 --> 00:08:01,607
- What do you got, a cold?
- And how.

91
00:08:01,608 --> 00:08:03,901
These hot-weather
colds can kill you.

92
00:08:03,902 --> 00:08:06,404
I can hardly touch my nose.
You know what I mean?

93
00:08:06,405 --> 00:08:10,032
I sure do. I just got over one.

94
00:08:10,033 --> 00:08:12,306
Aw, come on. Mr. Foreman,
let's go here, huh?

95
00:08:12,332 --> 00:08:14,579
Well, that guy's still
in the bathroom.

96
00:08:14,580 --> 00:08:17,498
Hey, what's new? I didn't get a
chance to see a paper this morning.

97
00:08:17,499 --> 00:08:18,666
Hmm?

98
00:08:18,667 --> 00:08:21,169
I was only wondering
how the market closed.

99
00:08:21,170 --> 00:08:23,963
You got a seat on the Exchange?

100
00:08:23,964 --> 00:08:25,798
I'm a broker.

101
00:08:25,799 --> 00:08:30,261
I run a messenger service...
the Beck and Call Company.

102
00:08:30,262 --> 00:08:32,471
The name is my wife's idea.

103
00:08:32,472 --> 00:08:36,184
Got 37 men working.
Started with nothing.

104
00:08:36,185 --> 00:08:39,437
Okay, men, let's
take our seats, huh?

105
00:08:42,524 --> 00:08:44,442
Yeah, we can all get outta
here pretty quick, huh?

106
00:08:44,443 --> 00:08:45,532
I don't know about the rest of you,

107
00:08:45,558 --> 00:08:47,737
but I happen to have tickets
to that ball game tonight.

108
00:08:47,738 --> 00:08:49,655
Yanks and Cleveland.

109
00:08:49,656 --> 00:08:51,532
Yeah, we got this kid,
Modjelewski, in there.

110
00:08:51,533 --> 00:08:53,284
Ooh, he's a real bull, this kid.

111
00:08:53,285 --> 00:08:55,494
You know... Phoom!

112
00:08:55,495 --> 00:08:57,830
A real jug handle. You know?

113
00:08:57,831 --> 00:09:00,166
Phoom!

114
00:09:00,167 --> 00:09:02,585
You're a real baseball fan,
aren't you? Huh? Yeah.

115
00:09:02,586 --> 00:09:04,128
Where do we sit here?

116
00:09:04,129 --> 00:09:07,298
Well, I thought we'd sit in order,
you know, by jury numbers.

117
00:09:07,299 --> 00:09:09,800
One, two, three, four, five...
so on, around the table.

118
00:09:09,801 --> 00:09:11,135
If that's okay with you gentlemen.

119
00:09:11,136 --> 00:09:12,303
- Sure.
- What's the difference?

120
00:09:12,304 --> 00:09:15,431
- I think it's reasonable to sit in order.
- Let it be.

121
00:09:15,432 --> 00:09:17,767
- Number 12. Do I sit down here?
- Yeah. That's 12. We go around...

122
00:09:17,768 --> 00:09:21,103
- We start with you. One, right?
- One, yeah. Two, three, four, five, six.

123
00:09:21,104 --> 00:09:23,522
What was your impression of
the prosecuting attorney?

124
00:09:23,523 --> 00:09:25,316
Okay. Two. You're two.

125
00:09:25,317 --> 00:09:26,567
I beg pardon?

126
00:09:26,568 --> 00:09:30,821
I thought he was really sharp, the way
he handled all those points one by one.

127
00:09:30,822 --> 00:09:34,033
Logical sequence.
I was very impressed.

128
00:09:34,034 --> 00:09:37,119
I think he... he did an expert job.

129
00:09:37,120 --> 00:09:40,206
A lot of drive too,
you know? Real drive.

130
00:09:40,207 --> 00:09:41,941
Okay, fellas, can we
hold it down a minute?

131
00:09:41,967 --> 00:09:42,375
Sure.

132
00:09:42,376 --> 00:09:44,043
Uh, fellas.

133
00:09:44,044 --> 00:09:47,605
Say, we'd like to get started.
Gentleman at the window.

134
00:09:49,174 --> 00:09:51,425
- We'd like to get started.
- Oh, I'm sorry.

135
00:09:51,426 --> 00:09:55,179
Pretty tough to figure, isn't it? Kid
kills his father... bing, just like that.

136
00:09:55,180 --> 00:09:57,848
Aw, listen, you analyze the figures,
you'll see it happens all the time.

137
00:09:57,849 --> 00:09:59,850
They let those kids
run wild up there.

138
00:09:59,851 --> 00:10:02,645
Well, maybe it serves 'em right.
You know what I mean?

139
00:10:02,646 --> 00:10:04,313
Is... Is everyone here?

140
00:10:04,314 --> 00:10:06,232
The old man is inside.

141
00:10:06,233 --> 00:10:08,943
Oh. Would you, uh,
knock on the door for him?

142
00:10:08,944 --> 00:10:10,987
You a Yankee fan?

143
00:10:10,988 --> 00:10:12,630
No. Baltimore.

144
00:10:13,448 --> 00:10:15,049
- Baltimore?
- Yeah.

145
00:10:16,243 --> 00:10:18,869
That's like being hit in the head
with a crowbar once a day.

146
00:10:20,539 --> 00:10:21,872
Who have they got?

147
00:10:21,873 --> 00:10:24,375
No, I mean, who have they got
besides good groundskeepers?

148
00:10:24,376 --> 00:10:26,002
Say, uh, we'd like to get started.

149
00:10:26,003 --> 00:10:29,146
Oh, forgive me, gentlemen.
I... I didn't mean to keep you waiting.

150
00:10:29,840 --> 00:10:31,716
Baltimore?

151
00:10:31,717 --> 00:10:34,593
Okay, gentlemen,
if I can have your attention.

152
00:10:34,594 --> 00:10:37,638
You fellas can handle this thing
any way that you want to.

153
00:10:37,639 --> 00:10:40,224
I'm, um... You know,
I'm not gonna make any rules.

154
00:10:40,225 --> 00:10:43,602
Uh, we can, well, discuss it
first and, uh, then vote on it.

155
00:10:43,603 --> 00:10:46,355
That's, of course, uh...
That's, uh, one way.

156
00:10:46,356 --> 00:10:49,400
And, uh, well, we can vote
on it right now, and...

157
00:10:49,401 --> 00:10:51,986
I think it's customary to
take a preliminary vote.

158
00:10:51,987 --> 00:10:55,656
Yeah, let's... Let's vote. Who knows?
Maybe we all can get outta here, huh?

159
00:10:57,451 --> 00:11:00,619
Okay, then I think that, uh...

160
00:11:00,620 --> 00:11:03,581
Of course you know that we have a
first-degree murder charge here...

161
00:11:03,582 --> 00:11:05,750
and if we vote the
accused guilty...

162
00:11:05,751 --> 00:11:09,086
uh, we've got to send
him to the chair.

163
00:11:09,087 --> 00:11:12,923
- Um, that's mandatory.
- I think we know that.

164
00:11:12,924 --> 00:11:14,759
- Let's see who's where.
- We might as well.

165
00:11:14,760 --> 00:11:18,654
- Okay. Uh, anyone doesn't want to vote?
- All right with me.

166
00:11:19,765 --> 00:11:24,435
Okay. Then, uh, just remember that this
has to be 12 to nothing either way.

167
00:11:24,436 --> 00:11:25,978
Um, that's the law.

168
00:11:25,979 --> 00:11:28,105
Okay, are we ready?

169
00:11:28,106 --> 00:11:31,208
Now, all those voting guilty,
please raise your hands.

170
00:11:35,113 --> 00:11:38,716
One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven...

171
00:11:39,951 --> 00:11:42,620
eight, nine, 10, 11.

172
00:11:42,621 --> 00:11:45,623
Okay. That's 11 guilty.

173
00:11:45,624 --> 00:11:47,224
Those voting not guilty.

174
00:11:48,293 --> 00:11:50,461
One. Right.

175
00:11:50,462 --> 00:11:52,855
That's 11 guilty. One not guilty.

176
00:11:53,673 --> 00:11:55,341
Well, now we know where we are.

177
00:11:55,342 --> 00:11:59,612
Boy, oh, boy. There's always one.

178
00:12:00,055 --> 00:12:02,431
So, what do we do now?

179
00:12:02,432 --> 00:12:04,350
Well, I guess we talk.

180
00:12:04,351 --> 00:12:05,768
Boy, oh, boy.

181
00:12:05,769 --> 00:12:07,703
You really think he's innocent?

182
00:12:11,066 --> 00:12:12,691
I don't know.

183
00:12:12,692 --> 00:12:15,653
I mean, you sat in court with the
rest of us. You heard what we did.

184
00:12:15,654 --> 00:12:17,863
The kid's a dangerous killer.
You could see it.

185
00:12:17,864 --> 00:12:19,573
He's 18 years old.

186
00:12:19,574 --> 00:12:21,742
Well, that's old enough. He...

187
00:12:21,743 --> 00:12:24,495
He stabbed his own father
four inches into the chest.

188
00:12:24,496 --> 00:12:26,831
They proved it a dozen
different ways in court.

189
00:12:26,832 --> 00:12:29,458
Would you like me to
list them for you?

190
00:12:29,459 --> 00:12:30,835
No.

191
00:12:30,836 --> 00:12:33,003
Then what do you want?

192
00:12:33,004 --> 00:12:36,006
- I just want to talk.
- What's there to talk about?

193
00:12:36,007 --> 00:12:37,425
Eleven men in here
think he's guilty.

194
00:12:37,426 --> 00:12:39,760
No one had to think about
it twice except you.

195
00:12:39,761 --> 00:12:43,055
I want to ask you something.
Do you believe his story?

196
00:12:43,056 --> 00:12:45,850
I don't know whether I believe
it or not. Maybe I don't.

197
00:12:45,851 --> 00:12:47,518
So how come you vote not guilty?

198
00:12:47,519 --> 00:12:49,520
Well, there were 11
votes for guilty.

199
00:12:49,521 --> 00:12:52,356
It's not easy to raise my hand
and send a boy off to die...

200
00:12:52,357 --> 00:12:54,525
without talking about it first.

201
00:12:54,526 --> 00:12:57,044
- Well, now, who says it's easy?
- No one.

202
00:12:58,238 --> 00:13:00,489
What, just because I voted fast?

203
00:13:00,490 --> 00:13:02,992
I honestly think the guy's guilty.

204
00:13:02,993 --> 00:13:05,870
You couldn't change my mind if
you talked for a hundred years.

205
00:13:05,871 --> 00:13:07,972
I'm not trying to change
your mind. It's just that...

206
00:13:08,457 --> 00:13:10,791
We're talking about
somebody's life here.

207
00:13:10,792 --> 00:13:12,960
We can't decide it in five minutes.
Supposing we're wrong.

208
00:13:12,961 --> 00:13:14,462
"Supposing we're wrong."

209
00:13:14,463 --> 00:13:16,547
Supposing this whole building
should fall down on my head.

210
00:13:16,548 --> 00:13:18,649
- You can suppose anything.
- That's right.

211
00:13:19,384 --> 00:13:21,218
Look, what's the difference
how long it takes?

212
00:13:21,219 --> 00:13:23,888
Suppose we do it in
five minutes. So what?

213
00:13:23,889 --> 00:13:26,098
Let's take an hour.

214
00:13:26,099 --> 00:13:28,117
The ball game doesn't
start till 8:00.

215
00:13:34,065 --> 00:13:35,983
Who's got something to say?

216
00:13:35,984 --> 00:13:37,485
I'm willing to sit for an hour.

217
00:13:37,486 --> 00:13:40,279
Great. I heard a pretty
good story last night.

218
00:13:40,280 --> 00:13:42,464
That's not why we're sitting here.

219
00:13:43,074 --> 00:13:46,719
All right, then you tell me.
What are we sitting here for?

220
00:13:47,871 --> 00:13:49,805
I don't know. Maybe no reason.

221
00:13:50,707 --> 00:13:54,251
Look, this kid's been kicked
around all of his life...

222
00:13:54,252 --> 00:13:58,255
you know, born in a slum,
mother dead since he was nine.

223
00:13:58,256 --> 00:14:00,549
He lived for a year and a half
in an orphanage when his...

224
00:14:00,550 --> 00:14:03,552
his father was serving a
jail term for forgery.

225
00:14:03,553 --> 00:14:05,971
It's not a very happy beginning.

226
00:14:05,972 --> 00:14:08,182
He's a... a wild, angry kid.

227
00:14:08,183 --> 00:14:09,975
That's all he's ever been.
And you know why?

228
00:14:09,976 --> 00:14:13,771
'Cause he's been hit on the head
by somebody once a day every day.

229
00:14:13,772 --> 00:14:16,065
He's had a... He's had a
pretty miserable 18 years.

230
00:14:16,066 --> 00:14:19,109
I... I just think we owe
him a few words. That's all.

231
00:14:19,110 --> 00:14:22,738
I don't mind telling you this, mister.
We don't owe him a thing.

232
00:14:22,739 --> 00:14:25,908
He got a fair trial, didn't he?
What do you think that trial cost?

233
00:14:25,909 --> 00:14:27,873
He's lucky he got it.
You know what I mean?

234
00:14:27,899 --> 00:14:31,497
- You know it.
- Now, look, we're all grown-ups in here.

235
00:14:31,498 --> 00:14:33,457
We heard the facts, didn't we?

236
00:14:33,458 --> 00:14:37,336
You're not gonna tell me that we're supposed
to believe this kid, knowing what he is.

237
00:14:37,337 --> 00:14:39,797
Listen, I've lived among
them all my life.

