You know what I mean, my friend?

1378
01:12:19,004 --> 01:12:22,356
- Who's got those cough drops?
- They're all gone, my friend.

1379
01:12:24,259 --> 01:12:26,593
Oh, boy. Look at that rain.

1380
01:12:26,594 --> 01:12:29,054
There goes your ball game.

1381
01:12:29,055 --> 01:12:31,557
It's only a shower.

1382
01:12:31,558 --> 01:12:33,809
Besides, they got the
infield covered.

1383
01:12:33,810 --> 01:12:37,079
Right. Say, could I see that
knife a second, please?

1384
01:12:39,774 --> 01:12:42,192
Well, we're still
tied up six to six.

1385
01:12:42,193 --> 01:12:44,278
Who's got a suggestion?

1386
01:12:44,279 --> 01:12:46,363
It's five after 6:00.
Let's get some dinner.

1387
01:12:46,364 --> 01:12:48,907
Why don't we wait till 7:00,
give it another hour, huh?

1388
01:12:48,908 --> 01:12:51,118
Okay with me.

1389
01:12:51,119 --> 01:12:53,370
Uh, there's something
I'd like to say.

1390
01:12:53,371 --> 01:12:56,999
I mean, it's been bothering me a little,
and as long as we're stuck.

1391
01:12:57,000 --> 01:13:00,961
Well, there was this whole business about
the stab wound and how it was made...

1392
01:13:00,962 --> 01:13:02,671
the downward angle of it, you know?

1393
01:13:02,672 --> 01:13:04,757
Don't tell me we're gonna
start with that again.

1394
01:13:04,758 --> 01:13:06,467
They've been over it and over it.

1395
01:13:06,468 --> 01:13:08,844
Well, I know they did,
but I don't go along with it.

1396
01:13:08,845 --> 01:13:12,931
Now, the boy was 5 feet 7
inches tall. His father was 6'2...

1397
01:13:12,932 --> 01:13:15,184
That's a difference
of seven inches.

1398
01:13:15,185 --> 01:13:17,936
It's a very awkward thing to stab
down into the chest of someone...

1399
01:13:17,937 --> 01:13:20,022
who's more than half a
foot taller than you are.

1400
01:13:20,023 --> 01:13:22,232
Give me that.

1401
01:13:22,233 --> 01:13:25,127
I'll give you a demonstration.
Somebody get up.

1402
01:13:26,404 --> 01:13:28,422
You...

1403
01:13:32,827 --> 01:13:35,621
I want you to watch this 'cause
I don't want to have to do it again.

1404
01:13:35,622 --> 01:13:38,457
I'll make myself about six or
seven inches shorter, okay?

1405
01:13:38,458 --> 01:13:41,685
- It's about right. Maybe a little more.
- Okay. A little more.

1406
01:13:49,385 --> 01:13:51,904
That's not funny.

1407
01:13:53,890 --> 01:13:57,826
Now, nobody's hurt. Right?

1408
01:13:58,394 --> 01:14:00,287
Right. Nobody hurt.

1409
01:14:03,650 --> 01:14:08,529
Now, this is the way I'd stab a
man who was taller than I was.

1410
01:14:08,530 --> 01:14:11,073
Look at the angle... down and in.

1411
01:14:11,074 --> 01:14:13,242
And this is the way it was done.

1412
01:14:13,243 --> 01:14:15,510
Now tell me I'm wrong.

1413
01:14:17,622 --> 01:14:21,125
- Down and in. I guess there's no argument.
- Hold it a minute, will ya?

1414
01:14:21,126 --> 01:14:23,060
Can you give me that?

1415
01:14:23,962 --> 01:14:25,963
Boy, I hate these things.

1416
01:14:25,964 --> 01:14:27,714
- Did you ever see a knife fight?
- No.

1417
01:14:27,715 --> 01:14:29,383
- You?
- No.

1418
01:14:29,384 --> 01:14:32,261
Anybody here ever
see a knife fight?

1419
01:14:32,262 --> 01:14:35,139
Well, I have. You know,
on my back stoop...

1420
01:14:35,140 --> 01:14:37,558
the lot across
the street, backyard.

1421
01:14:37,559 --> 01:14:40,060
Switchblades came with the
neighborhood where I lived.

1422
01:14:40,061 --> 01:14:43,397
It's funny I never thought of it before.
I guess you try to forget those things.

1423
01:14:43,398 --> 01:14:46,875
- How do you use a switchblade?
- Well, you'd never use it like this.

1424
01:14:48,528 --> 01:14:50,921
See, you use too much
time switching hands.

1425
01:14:52,574 --> 01:14:55,175
Here's how... underhanded.

1426
01:14:57,787 --> 01:15:00,914
Anyone who's ever used a switch knife
wouldn't handle it any other way.

1427
01:15:00,915 --> 01:15:03,625
- Are you sure?
- I'm sure.

1428
01:15:03,626 --> 01:15:05,544
That's why they're made
to open like that.

1429
01:15:05,545 --> 01:15:07,713
You'd say the boy was
pretty handy with a knife?

1430
01:15:08,256 --> 01:15:11,508
You think he could have made the kind
of wound that killed his father?

1431
01:15:11,509 --> 01:15:15,512
No. Not with the experience he'd had
all his life handling these things.

1432
01:15:15,513 --> 01:15:17,598
I feel he'd have gone
for him underhanded.

1433
01:15:17,599 --> 01:15:20,726
How do you know? Were you in the
room when the father was killed?

1434
01:15:20,727 --> 01:15:22,811
No. Neither was anybody else.

1435
01:15:22,812 --> 01:15:26,106
So what are you giving us all this
mumbo jumbo for? I don't believe it.

1436
01:15:26,107 --> 01:15:27,757
I don't think you can
determine what type of

1437
01:15:27,783 --> 01:15:29,443
wound the boy might or
might not have made...

1438
01:15:29,444 --> 01:15:32,154
simply because he knew
how to handle a knife.

1439
01:15:32,155 --> 01:15:34,573
What do you think?

1440
01:15:34,574 --> 01:15:36,742
- I don't know.
- What do you mean you don't know?

1441
01:15:36,743 --> 01:15:38,677
I don't know.

1442
01:15:42,790 --> 01:15:44,875
How about you?

1443
01:15:44,876 --> 01:15:46,787
I don't know about the rest
of them, but I'm getting a

1444
01:15:46,788 --> 01:15:48,712
little tired of this
yackety-yackin' back and forth.

1445
01:15:48,713 --> 01:15:52,257
It's gettin' us nowhere. So I
guess I'll have to break it up.

1446
01:15:52,258 --> 01:15:54,885
I change my vote to not guilty.

1447
01:15:54,886 --> 01:15:58,305
- You what?
- You heard me. I've had enough.

1448
01:15:58,306 --> 01:16:00,849
What do you mean you've had enough?
That's no answer!

1449
01:16:00,850 --> 01:16:04,895
Hey, listen. You just take care
of yourself, huh? You know?

1450
01:16:04,896 --> 01:16:08,941
He's right. That's not an answer.

1451
01:16:08,942 --> 01:16:11,985
What kind of a man are you?

1452
01:16:11,986 --> 01:16:15,197
You have sat here and voted
guilty with everyone else...

1453
01:16:15,198 --> 01:16:19,534
because there are some baseball tickets
burning a hole in your pocket.

1454
01:16:19,535 --> 01:16:23,889
And now you've changed your vote because
you say you're sick of all the talking here?

1455
01:16:24,791 --> 01:16:26,333
Now listen, buddy!

1456
01:16:26,334 --> 01:16:31,088
Who tells you that you have the right
to play like this with a man's life?

1457
01:16:31,089 --> 01:16:33,674
- Don't you care...
- Now wait a minute!

1458
01:16:33,675 --> 01:16:37,761
- You can't talk like that to me!
- I can talk like that to you.

1459
01:16:37,762 --> 01:16:39,721
If you want to vote not guilty...

1460
01:16:39,722 --> 01:16:42,182
then do it because you are
convinced the man is not guilty...

1461
01:16:42,183 --> 01:16:44,059
not because you've had enough.

1462
01:16:44,060 --> 01:16:46,728
And if you think he is guilty,
then vote that way.

1463
01:16:46,729 --> 01:16:50,023
Or don't you have the guts to
do what you think is right?

1464
01:16:50,024 --> 01:16:52,376
- Now listen.
- Guilty or not guilty?

1465
01:16:53,069 --> 01:16:56,755
- I told you, not guilty.
- Why?

1466
01:16:58,324 --> 01:17:00,033
Look, I don't have to...

1467
01:17:00,034 --> 01:17:03,245
You do have to! Say it! Why?

1468
01:17:03,246 --> 01:17:05,806
All right. I don't, uh,
think he's guilty.

1469
01:17:15,216 --> 01:17:16,925
I want another vote.

1470
01:17:16,926 --> 01:17:19,511
Okay. There's another
vote called for.

1471
01:17:19,512 --> 01:17:22,472
I guess the quickest way is a
show of hands. Anyone object?

1472
01:17:22,473 --> 01:17:25,492
Okay. All those voting not
guilty, raise your hands.

1473
01:17:26,311 --> 01:17:31,581
One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven...

1474
01:17:34,319 --> 01:17:36,086
eight.

1475
01:17:39,907 --> 01:17:42,134
Um, nine.

1476
01:17:43,036 --> 01:17:48,123
Um, all those voting guilty,
raise your hands.

1477
01:17:48,124 --> 01:17:50,584
One, two, three.

1478
01:17:50,585 --> 01:17:53,186
Well, the vote's nine to
three in favor of acquittal.

1479
01:17:54,088 --> 01:17:56,340
I don't understand you people!

1480
01:17:56,341 --> 01:17:58,592
I mean, all these picky little
points you keep bringing up.

1481
01:17:58,593 --> 01:18:02,012
They don't mean nothing!
You saw this kid just like I did.

1482
01:18:02,013 --> 01:18:05,599
You're not gonna tell me you believe that
phony story about losing the knife...

1483
01:18:05,600 --> 01:18:07,684
and that business about
being at the movies.

1484
01:18:07,685 --> 01:18:10,771
Look, you know how these
people lie. It's born in them.

1485
01:18:10,772 --> 01:18:12,898
I mean, what the heck.
I don't have to tell you.

1486
01:18:12,899 --> 01:18:14,941
They don't know what the truth is.

1487
01:18:14,942 --> 01:18:18,737
And let me tell you, they don't need any
real big reason to kill someone either.

1488
01:18:18,738 --> 01:18:20,572
No, sir.

1489
01:18:20,573 --> 01:18:23,700
They get drunk! Oh, they're
real big drinkers, all of 'em.

1490
01:18:23,701 --> 01:18:26,953
You know that. And bang...
someone's lying in the gutter.

1491
01:18:26,954 --> 01:18:30,040
Well, nobody's blaming them for it.
That's the way they are, by nature.

1492
01:18:30,041 --> 01:18:32,209
You know what I mean? Violent!

1493
01:18:32,210 --> 01:18:33,794
Where are you going?

1494
01:18:33,795 --> 01:18:36,897
Human life don't mean as much
to them as it does to us.

1495
01:18:37,799 --> 01:18:40,884
Look! They're lushing it up
and fighting all the time...

1496
01:18:40,885 --> 01:18:42,969
and if somebody gets killed,
so somebody gets killed!

1497
01:18:42,970 --> 01:18:44,429
They don't care!

1498
01:18:44,430 --> 01:18:46,723
Oh, sure, there's some
good things about 'em too.

1499
01:18:46,724 --> 01:18:48,767
Look, I'm the first
one to say that.

1500
01:18:48,768 --> 01:18:52,145
I've known a couple who were okay, but
that's the exception, you know what I mean?

1501
01:18:52,146 --> 01:18:55,982
Most of 'em, it's like they have
no feelings. They can do anything.

1502
01:18:55,983 --> 01:18:58,652
What's going on here?

1503
01:18:58,653 --> 01:19:00,779
I'm... I'm trying to tell ya...

1504
01:19:00,780 --> 01:19:02,864
you're making a big
mistake, you people.

1505
01:19:02,865 --> 01:19:05,967
This kid is a liar! I know it.
I know all about them.

1506
01:19:07,578 --> 01:19:09,830
Listen to me. They're no good.

1507
01:19:09,831 --> 01:19:12,265
There's not a one of
'em who's any good.

1508
01:19:14,210 --> 01:19:16,753
I mean, what...
What's happening in here?

1509
01:19:16,754 --> 01:19:19,105
I'm speaking my piece, and you...

1510
01:19:20,216 --> 01:19:21,983
Listen to me.

1511
01:19:22,969 --> 01:19:24,511
I...

1512
01:19:24,512 --> 01:19:27,055
We're... This kid on
trial here, his type...

1513
01:19:27,056 --> 01:19:29,157
Well, don't you know about them?

1514
01:19:31,018 --> 01:19:34,563
There's...
There's a danger here.

1515
01:19:34,564 --> 01:19:36,731
These people are dangerous.

1516
01:19:36,732 --> 01:19:39,860
They're... wild.

1517
01:19:39,861 --> 01:19:41,862
Listen to me.

1518
01:19:41,863 --> 01:19:44,281
- Listen.
- I have.

1519
01:19:44,282 --> 01:19:47,384
Now sit down and don't
open your mouth again.

1520
01:19:51,205 --> 01:19:54,057
I was only trying to... tell you.

1521
01:20:30,453 --> 01:20:34,848
It's always difficult to keep personal
prejudice out of a thing like this.

1522
01:20:35,875 --> 01:20:39,978
Wherever you run into it,
prejudice always obscures the truth.

1523
01:20:41,464 --> 01:20:43,924
I don't really know
what the truth is.

1524
01:20:43,925 --> 01:20:46,943
I don't suppose anybody
will ever really know.

1525
01:20:48,137 --> 01:20:52,182
Nine of us now seem to feel
that the defendant is innocent.

1526
01:20:52,183 --> 01:20:55,268
But we're just gambling
on probabilities.

1527
01:20:55,269 --> 01:20:57,312
We may be wrong.

1528
01:20:57,313 --> 01:20:59,773
We may be trying to let
a guilty man go free.

1529
01:20:59,774 --> 01:21:01,316
I don't know.

1530
01:21:01,317 --> 01:21:03,401
Nobody really can.

1531
01:21:03,402 --> 01:21:05,862
But we have a reasonable doubt...

1532
01:21:05,863 --> 01:21:09,449
and that's something that's
very valuable in our system.

1533
01:21:09,450 --> 01:21:14,095
No jury can declare a man
guilty unless it's sure.

1534
01:21:15,456 --> 01:21:17,916
We nine can't understand...

1535
01:21:17,917 --> 01:21:20,727
how you three are still so sure.

1536
01:21:21,462 --> 01:21:23,563
- Maybe you can tell us.
- I'll try.

1537
01:21:24,840 --> 01:21:28,426
You've made some excellent points, but I
still believe the boy is guilty of murder...

1538
01:21:28,427 --> 01:21:30,220
and I have two reasons.

1539
01:21:30,221 --> 01:21:33,431
One, the evidence given by the
woman across the street...

1540
01:21:33,432 --> 01:21:36,142
who actually saw the
murder committed.

1541
01:21:36,143 --> 01:21:38,812
As far as I'm concerned,
that's the most important testimony.

1542
01:21:38,813 --> 01:21:42,148
And two, the fact that she described
the stabbing by saying...

1543
01:21:42,149 --> 01:21:47,862
she saw the boy raise his arm over his head
and stab down into the father's chest.

1544
01:21:47,863 --> 01:21:49,990
She saw him do it the wrong way.

1545
01:21:49,991 --> 01:21:51,992
That's absolutely right.

1546
01:21:51,993 --> 01:21:54,661
Let's talk about this
woman for a moment.

1547
01:21:54,662 --> 01:21:57,831
She said she went to bed
about 11:00 that night.

1548
01:21:57,832 --> 01:22:01,501
Her bed was next to the window,
and she could look out while lying down...

1549
01:22:01,502 --> 01:22:05,672
and see directly into the
boy's room across the street.

1550
01:22:05,673 --> 01:22:08,383
She tossed and turned for over
an hour, unable to sleep.

1551
01:22:08,384 --> 01:22:12,637
Finally, she turned toward the window
at about 10 minutes after 12:00...

1552
01:22:12,638 --> 01:22:17,851
and, as she looked out, she saw the killing
through the windows of a passing el train.

1553
01:22:17,852 --> 01:22:20,645
She said the lights went out
immediately after the killing...

1554
01:22:20,646 --> 01:22:25,542
but that she got a good look at the boy
in the act of stabbing his father.

1555
01:22:26,444 --> 01:22:30,380
As far as I can see it,
this is unshakable testimony.

1556
01:22:31,032 --> 01:22:33,800
- Well, that's the whole case.
- What do you think?

1557
01:22:39,081 --> 01:22:40,849
How about you?

1558
01:22:42,376 --> 01:22:44,919
I don't know.

1559
01:22:44,920 --> 01:22:47,005
So much evidence to sift.

1560
01:22:47,006 --> 01:22:49,049
This is a pretty
complicated business.

1561
01:22:49,050 --> 01:22:52,927
Frankly, I don't see how you
can vote for acquittal.

1562
01:22:52,928 --> 01:22:55,347
It's not so easy to arrange
all the evidence in order.

1563
01:22:55,348 --> 01:22:57,474
You can throw out
all the other evidence!

1564
01:22:57,475 --> 01:23:01,144
The woman saw him do it!
What else do you want?

1565
01:23:01,145 --> 01:23:03,104
- Yeah, well, maybe...
- Let's vote on it.

1566
01:23:03,105 --> 01:23:05,357
Okay. There's another
vote called for.

1567
01:23:05,358 --> 01:23:07,275
Anybody object?

1568
01:23:07,276 --> 01:23:10,403
All right. I'm changing my vote.
He's guilty.

1569
01:23:10,404 --> 01:23:12,906
Anybody else?
The vote is eight to four.

1570
01:23:12,907 --> 01:23:16,576
Why is this such a personal
triumph for you... this one vote?

1571
01:23:16,577 --> 01:23:20,121
Okay. I say we're a hung jury.
I say we take it in to the judge.

1572
01:23:20,122 --> 01:23:22,916
How about it?
I want to hear arguments.

1573
01:23:22,917 --> 01:23:25,518
You, you're the leader of
the cause. What about it?

1574
01:23:27,672 --> 01:23:29,589
Let's go over it again.

1575
01:23:29,590 --> 01:23:31,591
We've been over it again!

1576
01:23:31,592 --> 01:23:34,170
The boy in the gray flannel
suit here is bouncin'

1577
01:23:34,171 --> 01:23:36,471
backwards and forwards
like a tennis ball.

1578
01:23:36,472 --> 01:23:40,408
No point in getting nasty and
trying to turn this into a contest.

1579
01:23:42,269 --> 01:23:43,812
Okay.

1580
01:23:43,813 --> 01:23:46,940
Maybe we can talk about setting
some kind of time limit.

1581
01:23:46,941 --> 01:23:49,167
Yeah, once around
for the deal, huh?

1582
01:23:49,777 --> 01:23:53,613
It's a quarter after 6:00.

1583
01:23:53,614 --> 01:23:55,657
Someone before mentioned 7:00.

1584
01:23:55,658 --> 01:23:58,118
I think that's a point at which
we might begin to discuss...

1585
01:23:58,119 --> 01:24:01,454
the question of whether
we're a hung jury or not.

1586
01:24:01,455 --> 01:24:03,223
Don't you feel well?

1587
01:24:04,458 --> 01:24:06,501
I feel perfectly well, thank you.

1588
01:24:06,502 --> 01:24:09,295
I was saying that 7:00
would be a reasonable time.

1589
01:24:09,296 --> 01:24:12,298
Uh, the reason I asked about
that was because, uh...

1590
01:24:12,299 --> 01:24:13,967
you were rubbing your nose like...

1591
01:24:13,968 --> 01:24:16,720
Oh, I'm sorry for interrupting...

1592
01:24:16,721 --> 01:24:20,014
but you made a gesture that
reminded me of something.

1593
01:24:20,015 --> 01:24:22,142
I'm trying to settle something
here. Do you mind?

1594
01:24:22,143 --> 01:24:24,244
Well, I think this is important.

1595
01:24:25,229 --> 01:24:27,105
Thank you.

1596
01:24:27,106 --> 01:24:29,816
Now then, I'm sure you'll
pardon me for this...

1597
01:24:29,817 --> 01:24:32,819
but I was wondering why you were
rubbing your nose like that.

1598
01:24:32,820 --> 01:24:34,571
Oh, come on, will ya?

1599
01:24:34,572 --> 01:24:38,825
At this point, I happen to be talking
to the gentleman sitting next to you!

1600
01:24:38,826 --> 01:24:42,162
Now, why were you rubbing
your nose like that?

1601
01:24:42,163 --> 01:24:46,332
Well, if it's any of your business, I was
rubbing it because it bothers me a little.

1602
01:24:46,333 --> 01:24:48,042
Oh. I'm sorry.

1603
01:24:48,043 --> 01:24:52,005
- Is it... Is it because of your eyeglasses?
- It is.

1604
01:24:52,006 --> 01:24:53,840
Now can we get on
to something else?

1605
01:24:53,841 --> 01:24:58,511
Your eyeglasses made those two deep
impressions on the sides of your nose.

1606
01:24:58,512 --> 01:25:00,764
I hadn't noticed that before.

1607
01:25:00,765 --> 01:25:04,350
- That must be annoying.
- It is very annoying.

1608
01:25:04,351 --> 01:25:06,352
Well, I wouldn't know about that.

1609
01:25:06,353 --> 01:25:09,773
I've never worn eyeglasses.
Twenty-twenty.

1610
01:25:09,774 --> 01:25:12,417
Listen, will you come on already
with the optometrist bit?

1611
01:25:14,236 --> 01:25:17,864
The woman who testified
that she saw the killing...

1612
01:25:17,865 --> 01:25:21,509
had those same marks on
the sides of her nose.

1613
01:25:22,411 --> 01:25:24,704
Holy smokes! You know, he's right.

1614
01:25:24,705 --> 01:25:26,456
Please.

1615
01:25:26,457 --> 01:25:30,293
Just give me a minute,
and I'll be finished.

1616
01:25:30,294 --> 01:25:33,213
I don't know if anyone else
noticed that about her.

1617
01:25:33,214 --> 01:25:37,191
I didn't think of it then,
but I've been going over her face...

1618
01:25:38,135 --> 01:25:40,345
in my mind.

1619
01:25:40,346 --> 01:25:42,447
She had those same marks.

1620
01:25:43,349 --> 01:25:47,619
- She kept rubbing them in court.
- He's right. She did do that a lot.

1621
01:25:48,562 --> 01:25:53,316
This woman was about, uh...
about 45 years old.

1622
01:25:53,317 --> 01:25:57,362
She was making a tremendous
effort to look 35...

1623
01:25:57,363 --> 01:25:59,656
for her first public appearance.

1624
01:25:59,657 --> 01:26:02,992
Heavy makeup, dyed hair...

1625
01:26:02,993 --> 01:26:06,955
brand-new clothes that should have
been worn by a younger woman.

1626
01:26:06,956 --> 01:26:08,706
No glasses.

1627
01:26:08,707 --> 01:26:10,458
No, women do that.

1628
01:26:10,459 --> 01:26:12,961
See if you can get the
mental picture of it.

1629
01:26:12,962 --> 01:26:14,879
What do you mean, no glasses?

1630
01:26:14,880 --> 01:26:17,674
How do you know whether she wore glasses?
Just 'cause she was rubbing her nose?

1631
01:26:17,675 --> 01:26:19,968
Now, she had those
marks. I saw 'em.

1632
01:26:19,969 --> 01:26:21,970
So what? What do ya
think that means?

1633
01:26:21,971 --> 01:26:24,238
Listen, I'm getting so sick
of your yelling in here!

1634
01:26:24,264 --> 01:26:25,265
Come on. Forget it.

1635
01:26:25,266 --> 01:26:28,351
Hey, listen. Listen, he's right.
I saw them too.

1636
01:26:28,352 --> 01:26:31,563
I was the closest one to her. She had these,
these things on the side of her nose.

1637
01:26:31,564 --> 01:26:34,858
- What do you call those on the side?
- Well, what point are you making here?

1638
01:26:34,859 --> 01:26:38,820
She had dyed hair, marks on her nose.
Well, what does that mean?

1639
01:26:38,821 --> 01:26:43,216
Could those marks be made by
anything other than eyeglasses?

1640
01:26:46,704 --> 01:26:49,122
No, they couldn't.

1641
01:26:49,123 --> 01:26:51,224
I didn't see any marks!

1642
01:26:52,751 --> 01:26:54,544
I did.

1643
01:26:54,545 --> 01:26:57,171
Strange, but I didn't
think about it before.

1644
01:26:57,172 --> 01:26:59,382
Well, what about the lawyer?
Why didn't he say something?

1645
01:26:59,383 --> 01:27:02,385
There are 12 people in here
concentrating on this case.

1646
01:27:02,386 --> 01:27:04,554
Eleven of us didn't
think of it either.

1647
01:27:04,555 --> 01:27:07,807
Well, what about the district attorney?
Do you think he'd pull a trick like that?

1648
01:27:07,808 --> 01:27:09,784
Have her testify
without her glasses?

1649
01:27:09,810 --> 01:27:11,716
Did you ever see a woman who
had to wear glasses and

1650
01:27:11,717 --> 01:27:13,813
didn't want to because she
thinks they spoil her looks?

1651
01:27:13,814 --> 01:27:17,400
Okay. She had marks on her nose.

1652
01:27:17,401 --> 01:27:21,154
I'm giving you that.
From glasses, right?

1653
01:27:21,155 --> 01:27:25,408
She didn't want to wear 'em out of the house
so people would think she's gorgeous.

1654
01:27:25,409 --> 01:27:30,079
But when she saw this kid killing his
father, she was in the house alone.

1655
01:27:30,080 --> 01:27:32,373
That's all.

1656
01:27:32,374 --> 01:27:36,477
- Do you wear glasses when you go to bed?
- No, I don't.

1657
01:27:38,088 --> 01:27:40,089
No one wears eyeglasses to bed.

1658
01:27:40,090 --> 01:27:43,176
It's logical to assume that she wasn't
wearing them when she was in bed...

1659
01:27:43,177 --> 01:27:45,011
tossing and turning,
trying to fall asleep.

1660
01:27:45,012 --> 01:27:47,430
- How do you know?
- I don't know! I'm guessing.

1661
01:27:47,431 --> 01:27:49,974
I'm also guessing that she probably
didn't put her glasses on...

1662
01:27:49,975 --> 01:27:52,185
when she turned to look
casually out of the window.

1663
01:27:52,186 --> 01:27:55,021
And she herself testified the killing
took place just as she looked out.

1664
01:27:55,022 --> 01:27:56,481
The lights went off a
split second later.

1665
01:27:56,507 --> 01:27:58,149
She couldn't have had
time to put them on then.

1666
01:27:58,150 --> 01:27:59,859
- Wait a second.
- Here's another guess.

1667
01:27:59,860 --> 01:28:04,030
Maybe she honestly thought she saw the boy
kill his father. I say she only saw a blur.

1668
01:28:04,031 --> 01:28:07,700
How do you know what she saw?
How does he know all that?

1669
01:28:07,701 --> 01:28:10,536
How do you know what kind of glasses
she wore? Maybe they were sunglasses.

1670
01:28:10,537 --> 01:28:13,247
Maybe she was farsighted.
What do you know about it?

1671
01:28:13,248 --> 01:28:16,584
I only know the woman's
eyesight is in question now.

1672
01:28:16,585 --> 01:28:22,799
She had to be able to identify a person
60 feet away, at night, without glasses.

1673
01:28:22,800 --> 01:28:25,259
You can't send someone off to
die on evidence like that.

1674
01:28:25,260 --> 01:28:27,345
Oh, don't give me that.

1675
01:28:27,346 --> 01:28:29,597
Don't you think the woman
might have made a mistake?

1676
01:28:29,598 --> 01:28:32,100
- No.
- It's not possible?

1677
01:28:32,101 --> 01:28:33,826
No, it's not possible.

1678
01:28:36,689 --> 01:28:38,706
Is it possible?

1679
01:28:39,733 --> 01:28:41,501
Not guilty.

1680
01:28:45,572 --> 01:28:48,324
Do you think he's guilty?

1681
01:28:48,325 --> 01:28:50,426
I think he's guilty.

1682
01:28:53,080 --> 01:28:54,847
Do you?

1683
01:28:57,626 --> 01:29:00,753
No. I'm convinced.

1684
01:29:00,754 --> 01:29:02,422
Not guilty.

1685
01:29:02,423 --> 01:29:04,298
What's the matter with you?

1686
01:29:04,299 --> 01:29:06,300
I have a reasonable doubt now.

1687
01:29:06,301 --> 01:29:07,927
Eleven to one.

1688
01:29:07,928 --> 01:29:10,930
Well, what about all the other evidence?
What about all that stuff?

1689
01:29:10,931 --> 01:29:13,099
The knife, the whole business!

1690
01:29:13,100 --> 01:29:16,119
Well, you said we could throw
out all the other evidence.

1691
01:29:21,775 --> 01:29:24,043
Well, what do we do now?

1692
01:29:26,947 --> 01:29:28,698
You're alone.

1693
01:29:28,699 --> 01:29:32,635
I don't care whether
I'm alone or not! It's my right.

1694
01:29:35,706 --> 01:29:37,974
It's your right.

1695
01:29:47,009 --> 01:29:49,527
Well, what do you want?
I say he's guilty.

1696
01:29:51,055 --> 01:29:54,490
- We want to hear your arguments.
- I gave you my arguments.

1697
01:29:55,392 --> 01:29:57,602
We're not convinced.

1698
01:29:57,603 --> 01:30:00,480
We want to hear them again.

1699
01:30:00,481 --> 01:30:02,582
We have as much time as it takes.

1700
01:30:08,155 --> 01:30:12,700
Everything... Every single thing
that took place in that courtroom...

1701
01:30:12,701 --> 01:30:14,702
but I mean everything...
says he's guilty.

1702
01:30:14,703 --> 01:30:17,263
What do you think,
I'm an idiot or something?

1703
01:30:18,832 --> 01:30:21,000
Why don't you take that
stuff about the old man?

1704
01:30:21,001 --> 01:30:24,270
The old man who lived there
and heard everything.

1705
01:30:25,839 --> 01:30:27,590
Or this business about the knife.

1706
01:30:27,591 --> 01:30:29,675
What? 'Cause he found another
one exactly like it?

1707
01:30:29,676 --> 01:30:33,096
The old man saw him right
there on the stairs!

1708
01:30:33,097 --> 01:30:36,032
What's the difference how
many seconds it was?

1709
01:30:37,101 --> 01:30:39,202
Every single thing.

1710
01:30:40,521 --> 01:30:43,773
The knife falling through
a hole in his pocket.

1711
01:30:43,774 --> 01:30:47,193
You can't prove he
didn't get to the door.

1712
01:30:47,194 --> 01:30:49,695
Sure, you can take all the time,
hobble around the room.

1713
01:30:49,696 --> 01:30:52,381
But you can't prove it!

1714
01:30:54,201 --> 01:30:57,912
And what about this business
of the el and the movies?

1715
01:30:57,913 --> 01:31:01,040
There's a phony deal
if I ever heard one.

1716
01:31:01,041 --> 01:31:05,336
I'll bet ya $5,000 I'd
remember the movies I saw.

1717
01:31:05,337 --> 01:31:07,672
I'm telling ya, everything
that's gone on...

1718
01:31:07,673 --> 01:31:11,592
has been twisted and turned!

1719
01:31:11,593 --> 01:31:13,761
This business with the glasses?

1720
01:31:13,762 --> 01:31:19,392
How do you know she didn't have them on?
This woman testified in open court!

1721
01:31:19,393 --> 01:31:23,437
And what about hearing
the kid yell, huh?

1722
01:31:23,438 --> 01:31:26,791
I'm telling ya, I've got
all the facts here.

1723
01:31:27,860 --> 01:31:29,835
Here. Ah...

1724
01:31:32,114 --> 01:31:34,715
Well, that's it!
That's the whole case.

1725
01:31:41,832 --> 01:31:43,516
Well?

1726
01:31:45,711 --> 01:31:47,812
Say something!

1727
01:31:52,843 --> 01:31:56,529
You lousy bunch of bleeding hearts.

1728
01:31:57,097 --> 01:31:59,098
You're not gonna intimidate me.

1729
01:31:59,099 --> 01:32:01,701
I'm entitled to my opinion.

1730
01:32:04,980 --> 01:32:09,375
Rotten kids.
You work your life out!

1731
01:32:14,114 --> 01:32:16,173
I can't keep...

1732
01:32:20,746 --> 01:32:22,513
No.

1733
01:32:26,293 --> 01:32:28,227
Not guilty.

1734
01:32:31,506 --> 01:32:33,274
Not guilty.

1735
01:32:36,178 --> 01:32:37,887
Not...

1736
01:32:48,357 --> 01:32:50,624
Um, we're ready now.

1737
01:34:44,181 --> 01:34:45,948
Hey!

1738
01:34:50,187 --> 01:34:51,937
What's your name?

1739
01:34:51,938 --> 01:34:53,522
Davis.

1740
01:34:53,523 --> 01:34:55,541
My name's McCardle.

1741
01:34:57,778 --> 01:34:59,528
Well, so long.

1742
01:34:59,529 --> 01:35:01,130
So long.
